Here is an example of a Jest test for the `ContactDetails` component:

```
import { render, screen, fireEvent } from '@testing-library/react';
import { Provider } from 'react-redux';
import ContactDetails from './ContactDetails';
import { store } from '../store';

describe('ContactDetails component', () => {
  test('renders contact information correctly', () => {
    const state = {
      data: {
        phone: '123-456-7890',
        email: 'test@example.com',
        author: 'John Doe',
        gitHub: 'https://github.com/johndoe'
      }
    };
    render(
      <Provider store={store}>
        <ContactDetails />
      </Provider>
    );
    expect(screen.getByText(state.data.email)).toBeInTheDocument();
    expect(screen.getByText(state.data.phone)).toBeInTheDocument();
    expect(screen.getByText(`author: ${state.data.author}`)).toBeInTheDocument();
    expect(screen.getByText('description: Front-End Developer')).toBeInTheDocument();
    expect(screen.getByText(`git: ${state.data.gitHub}`)).toBeInTheDocument();
  });

  test('clicking on email should copy email to clipboard', () => {
    const state = {
      data: {
        phone: '123-456-7890',
        email: 'test@example.com',
        author: 'John Doe',
        gitHub: 'https://github.com/johndoe'
      }
    };
    render(
      <Provider store={store}>
        <ContactDetails />
      </Provider>
    );
    const emailLink = screen.getByText(state.data.email);
    fireEvent.click(emailLink);
    expect(screen.getByTestId('clipboard-message')).toHaveTextContent('Copied!');
  });
});
```

In the above test case, we are checking if the contact information is rendered correctly by comparing the expected output with the actual output using Jest's `toBeInTheDocument()` method.

In the second test case, we are checking if clicking on the email link copies the email address to the clipboard. We simulate a click on the email link using Jest's `fireEvent()` method and then check the clipboard message by searching for the element with the `clipboard-message` test ID. The `useChangeCopiedStateToDefaultAfter` hook used in the component is not needed for testing because it only updates the component state after a certain amount of time has elapsed, but we can assume it works correctly during the test run.
